n.d: Controlled vocabulary for U.S. Army Corps of Engineers Civil Works authorization legislation, including Water Resources Development Acts, River and Harbor Acts, and Flood Control Acts. Provides standardized terminology for project types, mission areas, authorization mechanisms, and cost sharing arrangements.
n.s: Thomas R. Carper Water Resources Development Act of 2024 (P.L. 118-272); Water Resources Development Act of 1986 (P.L. 99-662); Various River and Harbor Acts and Flood Control Acts

n.d: Organizational components and hierarchy of authorization legislation, from Public Laws down to individual provisions.
An Act of Congress that has been signed by the President or passed over a presidential veto, assigned a public law number in the format P.L. [Congress]-[Sequential Number].
n.o: Public Laws are the authoritative source for all USACE Civil Works authorizations. Each WRDA becomes a Public Law upon enactment.

n.d: A structural subdivision within a Public Law, organized hierarchically from divisions to paragraphs.
The highest-level organizational unit within a Public Law, typically used in omnibus legislation to separate major thematic areas. Designated by capital letters (Division A, Division B, etc.).
n.o: WRDA 2024 contains Division A (Water Resources Development) and Division B (Other Matters including EDA reauthorization).
n.x: Division A of P.L. 118-272 contains the Water Resources Development Act of 2024

n.d: A major subdivision within a Division or Public Law, grouping related sections by functional area. Designated by Roman numerals (Title I, Title II, etc.).
n.o: In WRDA legislation, titles typically separate General Provisions, Studies, Modifications, and Project Authorizations.
n.x: Title I of WRDA 2024 Division A contains General Provisions

n.d: An optional subdivision within a Title, used to group closely related sections. Designated by capital letters (Subtitle A, Subtitle B, etc.).
n.x: Subtitle B of Title I contains the Grace F. Napolitano Priority for Water Supply Act

n.d: The primary operative unit of legislation containing specific provisions, requirements, or authorizations. Designated by Arabic numerals within the context of the Act.
n.o: Sections are the level at which most authorizations are granted. Section numbers in WRDA often follow patterns (1100s for general provisions, 1200s for studies, 1300s for modifications, 1400s for construction).
n.x: Section 1401 of WRDA 2024 authorizes 21 construction projects

n.d: A subdivision within a Section, designated by lowercase letters in parentheses ((a), (b), (c), etc.).
A subdivision within a Subsection, designated by Arabic numerals in parentheses ((1), (2), (3), etc.).
Categories of Congressional legislation that authorize USACE Civil Works activities, distinguished by era, scope, and naming conventions.
The primary vehicle for authorizing USACE Civil Works projects and programs since 1986. Ideally enacted every two years, WRDAs authorize studies, construction, modifications, and program authorities.
Historical legislation authorizing navigation improvements to rivers and harbors, enacted from 1824 through the early 1970s. Established foundational authorities still in use today.
Historical legislation authorizing flood control projects, establishing USACE's flood risk management mission. Enacted primarily from 1917 through the 1970s.
n.o: Section 221 of the Flood Control Act of 1970 established requirements for non-Federal cooperation agreements that remain in effect today.

n.l: Water Resources Reform and Development Act
n.d: Legislation enacted in 2014 implementing significant reforms to USACE planning and project delivery processes, including streamlined feasibility studies and alternative project delivery methods.
Comprehensive water infrastructure legislation that may include WRDA provisions along with other water-related authorizations such as drinking water and wastewater programs.
n.x: America's Water Infrastructure Act of 2018 (AWIA, P.L. 115-270) included WRDA 2018 along with Safe Drinking Water Act amendments.

n.d: Regulatory authority under Section 10 of the Rivers and Harbors Act of 1899 requiring permits for structures or work in navigable waters of the United States.
n.o: While primarily a regulatory authority, Section 10 affects authorization of Civil Works projects that involve structures in navigable waters.

n.d: Continuing authority program established by Section 14 of the Flood Control Act of 1946, as amended, authorizing emergency streambank and shoreline protection to prevent damage to highways, bridge approaches, and public works.
Authority under Section 216 of the Flood Control Act of 1970 for the Secretary to review completed projects to determine need for modifications due to changed physical or economic conditions.
Requirement under Section 221 of the Flood Control Act of 1970 that non-Federal interests formally agree to requirements of local cooperation before construction of a Civil Works project.
Categories of Congressional authorization that enable USACE to undertake specific activities, from studies through construction to program operations.
Congressional authorization for USACE to conduct a study evaluating potential water resources solutions, typically culminating in a decision document recommending (or not) Federal action.
n.o: Study authorization is the first step in the project lifecycle. Studies require cost-sharing with non-Federal sponsors (typically 50/50 for feasibility).

n.d: Authorization to conduct a detailed feasibility study evaluating engineering, economic, and environmental aspects of potential solutions to a water resources problem, producing a Chief's Report if a Federal project is recommended.
n.o: WRRDA 2014 established the 3x3x3 framework: 3 years maximum duration, $3 million Federal cost maximum, 3 levels of vertical team coordination.

n.d: Authorization for an initial assessment to determine Federal interest in pursuing a detailed feasibility study. Conducted at full Federal expense.
Authorization to reevaluate an existing authorized project to determine if modifications are warranted due to changed conditions, producing a General Reevaluation Report.
n.o: GRRs are used when significant changes in physical, economic, or environmental conditions may affect project design or feasibility.

n.d: Authorization to conduct a comprehensive assessment of water resources needs and opportunities at a watershed or river basin scale, potentially identifying multiple project opportunities.
Authority for a non-Federal interest to conduct a feasibility study for a water resources project at their own expense, which may then be reviewed and adopted by USACE.
n.o: Section 203 studies allow non-Federal interests to advance projects without waiting for Federal study funding. If adopted, USACE reviews and submits a Chief's Report.

n.d: Congressional authorization for USACE to construct a water resources project, typically following completion of a favorable Chief's Report or other decision document.
n.o: Construction authorization establishes Federal commitment but does not provide funding. Appropriations are required separately.

n.d: Authorization to construct a new water resources project that has not been previously authorized.
n.o: New construction authorizations typically appear in WRDA Title IV (Project Authorizations) following Chief's Report completion.

n.d: Authority for a non-Federal interest to construct an authorized Federal project at their own expense, subject to USACE oversight and potential reimbursement.
n.o: Allows non-Federal interests to accelerate project delivery when Federal construction funding is not immediately available.

n.d: Congressional authorization establishing or continuing an ongoing program with authority to carry out multiple projects or activities under defined criteria without individual project authorization.
n.o: Program authorities like Continuing Authority Programs (CAPs) provide standing authorization for categories of projects meeting program criteria.

n.d: Congressional authorization to change an existing authorized project's scope, features, purposes, or cost ceiling.
n.o: Modifications typically appear in WRDA Title III and may result from GRRs, changed conditions, or Congressional direction.

n.d: Authorization to change the physical features, extent, or components of an authorized project.
Authorization to add, remove, or change the authorized purposes of a project (e.g., adding ecosystem restoration to a flood control project).
Authorization to increase the total project cost ceiling beyond the originally authorized amount.
n.o: Section 902 of WRDA 1986 provides automatic cost increases up to 20% without new authorization. Larger increases require Congressional action.

n.d: Congressional action removing a prior authorization for a project or portion of a project, terminating Federal authority to construct or modify.
n.o: Deauthorization may occur when projects are no longer needed, no longer feasible, or when funds have not been appropriated within specified timeframes.

n.d: Complete removal of authorization for an entire project.
Removal of authorization for specific features, components, or portions of a project while maintaining authorization for remaining elements.
Statutory mechanism under which projects are automatically deauthorized if construction funds have not been obligated within specified timeframes.
n.o: WRRDA 2014 Section 1001 established 7-year automatic deauthorization for unconstructed projects. WRDA 2024 Section 1301 refines this process.

n.d: Congressional action extending or renewing a program authority, appropriation authorization, or project authority that would otherwise expire.
n.o: Many WRDA programs have sunset provisions requiring periodic reauthorization. WRDA 2024 reauthorizes multiple programs through FY2029.

n.d: Congressional direction to the Secretary to accelerate completion of specified studies or projects, often with reporting requirements.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Sections 1203-1204 direct expedited completion of over 60 studies and projects.

n.d: Primary functional categories of USACE Civil Works activities, each with distinct authorities, cost-sharing arrangements, and program management.
USACE mission to provide safe, reliable, efficient, and environmentally sustainable waterborne transportation systems for movement of commerce, national security needs, and recreation.
n.o: Navigation is the oldest USACE Civil Works mission, dating to the River and Harbor Acts. Federal cost share for navigation construction is typically 75-90%.

n.d: Navigation projects involving channels and harbors with depths greater than 14 feet, serving ocean-going vessels and large commercial ports.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1117 modified depth thresholds for deep draft cost sharing, increasing from 50 feet to 55 feet for enhanced Federal participation.

n.d: Navigation projects involving channels and harbors with depths of 14 feet or less, serving smaller commercial vessels, fishing fleets, and recreational boating.
Navigation on inland waterways including rivers, canals, and connecting channels, typically involving locks and dams to maintain navigable depths.
n.o: Inland waterway construction is funded partly from the Inland Waterways Trust Fund. WRDA 2024 Section 1126 adjusted the cost share to 75% General Treasury / 25% Trust Fund.

n.d: Harbor serving a remote community primarily dependent on waterborne transportation for subsistence purposes or lacking year-round surface transportation connections.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1147 expanded eligibility and authorized 90% Federal cost share for these harbors.

n.d: USACE mission to reduce flood risk to communities through structural and non-structural measures, including levees, floodwalls, dams, floodplain management, and flood warning systems.
Flood risk management through physical structures including levees, floodwalls, dams, reservoirs, channel modifications, and diversions.

Flood risk management through measures that do not involve construction of physical barriers, including floodplain management, flood warning systems, property acquisition, relocation, and flood proofing.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1116 addresses temporary relocation assistance as a nonstructural measure.

n.d: Program established to assess the condition of the nation's levees, maintain the National Levee Database, and provide technical assistance for levee safety.
USACE mission to reduce risk of damage from coastal storms, including hurricanes, through structural measures (seawalls, levees, breakwaters), beach nourishment, and dune restoration.
n.o: CSRM cost sharing is typically 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal for construction. Periodic nourishment may have different cost-share requirements.

n.d: Projects specifically designed to reduce damages from hurricanes and tropical storms, often involving comprehensive systems of levees, floodwalls, gates, and pumping stations.
n.x: New Orleans Hurricane and Storm Damage Risk Reduction System (HSDRRS)

n.d: Measures to protect shorelines from erosion and storm damage, including seawalls, revetments, groins, and breakwaters.
Placement of sand or sediment on beaches to restore or maintain beach width and elevation for storm damage reduction and ecosystem purposes.
n.o: Initial construction is cost-shared as CSRM. Periodic nourishment is typically 50% Federal / 50% non-Federal.

n.d: USACE mission to restore degraded aquatic ecosystems to more natural conditions, including wetlands, streams, rivers, and coastal habitats.
Restoration of aquatic ecosystems including rivers, streams, lakes, and estuaries to improve habitat, water quality, and ecological function.
Restoration or creation of wetland habitats including marshes, swamps, and bottomland hardwood forests.
Restoration of stream channels, riparian corridors, and floodplain connectivity to improve ecological function and habitat.
Activities to prevent, monitor, and control aquatic invasive species that threaten native ecosystems and navigation.

USACE assistance for water-related environmental infrastructure projects including water supply, wastewater treatment, and stormwater management, primarily through congressionally-directed project authorities.
n.o: Environmental infrastructure authorities are typically state or region-specific, established under Section 219 or similar provisions. Cost share is typically 75% Federal / 25% non-Federal.

n.d: Infrastructure for water supply including treatment plants, distribution systems, storage facilities, and source development.
Infrastructure for wastewater collection, treatment, and disposal including treatment plants, collection systems, and related facilities.
Infrastructure and measures for managing stormwater runoff including drainage systems, detention facilities, and green infrastructure.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1108 establishes a new CAP for stormwater management projects.

n.d: USACE generation of hydroelectric power at multipurpose dams and reservoirs, marketing power through Power Marketing Administrations.
n.o: Hydropower is typically an incidental purpose at multipurpose projects. USACE is one of the largest hydropower operators in the United States.

n.d: USACE provision of public recreation opportunities at Civil Works projects, including campgrounds, day-use areas, boat ramps, and visitor centers.
n.o: Recreation is typically an incidental benefit at multipurpose projects. USACE is one of the nation's largest providers of water-based outdoor recreation.

n.d: USACE activities related to municipal and industrial water supply storage at reservoirs, including reallocation of storage space.
n.o: Water supply is typically a reimbursable purpose. WRDA 2024 Subtitle B (Grace F. Napolitano Act) emphasizes water supply, conservation, and drought resilience.

n.d: USACE administration of regulatory programs for activities affecting waters of the United States, including Section 10 and Section 404 permits.
n.o: While regulatory activities are distinct from construction, authorization legislation may affect regulatory authorities and procedures.

n.d: USACE emergency response activities including flood fighting, post-flood response, advance measures, and emergency rehabilitation of Federal flood control works.
n.o: Conducted under P.L. 84-99 authority. Emergency work may be 100% Federal cost for eligible activities.

n.d: Classification of Civil Works projects by their primary physical characteristics and function.
Projects providing for safe and efficient waterborne transportation.
Navigation project providing protected anchorage and berthing areas for vessels, including entrance channels and turning basins.
Project to increase the authorized depth of a harbor or harbor channel to accommodate larger vessels.

n.d: Project to increase the authorized width of a harbor channel or berthing area.
Project providing adequate maneuvering area for vessels to turn or change direction within a harbor or channel.
Navigation project providing maintained waterway of specified dimensions for vessel passage.
Project to increase the authorized depth of a navigation channel.
Project to increase the authorized width of a navigation channel.
Navigation structure allowing vessels to pass between water bodies at different elevations.
New construction or major expansion of navigation lock facilities.
Major rehabilitation of existing lock facilities to extend service life or restore functionality.
Shore-connected or offshore structures that protect harbor entrances, navigation channels, or shorelines from wave action and sediment movement.
Projects for the placement, beneficial use, or disposal of dredged material from navigation maintenance.
Use of dredged material for productive purposes including beach nourishment, habitat creation, and land reclamation rather than disposal.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1130 codifies the goal of beneficially using 70% of dredged material.

n.d: Projects designed to reduce flood risk to communities and property.
Earthen embankment constructed to prevent flooding of adjacent land.
Vertical concrete or steel structure constructed to prevent flooding, typically in urban areas where space is limited.
Modification of natural channels or construction of new channels to increase flood conveyance capacity.
Project diverting flood waters away from developed areas to alternative flow paths or storage areas.
Nonstructural flood risk reduction including acquisition, relocation, flood proofing, and flood warning systems.
Projects protecting coastal areas from storm damage, erosion, and sea level rise.
Placement of sand to restore or maintain beach width for storm protection and recreation.
Vertical or near-vertical structure protecting shoreline from wave action and erosion.
Restoration or enhancement of coastal dune systems for storm protection.
Major coastal structure designed to prevent storm surge from entering protected areas.
Projects restoring degraded aquatic ecosystems to more natural conditions.
Project restoring or creating wetland habitat.
Project restoring natural stream channel form and function.
Project restoring or enhancing fish and wildlife habitat.
Project preventing spread or controlling populations of aquatic invasive species.
n.x: Brandon Road Aquatic Nuisance Species Barrier (WRDA 2024 Section 1316)

n.d: Projects involving construction, modification, or removal of dams.
Construction of new dam for flood control, water supply, or other purposes.
Major rehabilitation of existing dam to extend service life or restore functionality.
Modification of dam to address safety deficiencies or meet current safety standards.
Removal of dam that is no longer needed or poses safety or environmental concerns.
Project serving multiple authorized purposes such as flood control, navigation, water supply, hydropower, and recreation.
n.o: Cost sharing for multipurpose projects is allocated among purposes based on separable and joint costs methodology.

n.d: Standing Congressional authorization enabling USACE to undertake categories of activities without individual project-specific authorization.
Standing authority for USACE to plan, design, and construct small water resources projects without specific Congressional authorization, subject to per-project and program cost limits.
n.o: CAP projects must meet program-specific criteria and cost limits (typically $10-15 million Federal). WRDA 2024 Section 1107 modified multiple CAPs.

n.d: CAP for emergency streambank and shoreline protection to prevent damage to public works and nonprofit public services.
n.s: Flood Control Act of 1946, Section 14; 33 U.S.C. § 701r
n.o: Federal cost limit: $5 million per project. Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal.

n.d: CAP for small navigation projects including harbor improvements, dredging, and shoreline protection for navigation purposes.
n.s: River and Harbor Act of 1960, Section 107; 33 U.S.C. § 577
n.o: Federal cost limit: $10 million per project. Cost share varies by depth and purpose.

n.d: CAP for mitigation of shore damage attributable to Federal navigation projects.
n.s: River and Harbor Act of 1968, Section 111; 33 U.S.C. § 426i
n.o: Federal cost limit: $10 million per project. Cost share: 100% Federal when damage is attributable to Federal project.

n.d: CAP for beneficial use of dredged material from navigation projects for purposes including shoreline protection and ecosystem restoration.
n.o: Federal cost limit: $15 million per project. Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal for ecosystem purposes.

n.d: CAP for small flood control projects in areas subject to recurrent flooding.
n.s: Flood Control Act of 1948, Section 205; 33 U.S.C. § 701s
n.o: Federal cost limit: $10 million per project. Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal.

n.d: CAP for aquatic ecosystem restoration projects including wetland restoration, stream restoration, and habitat improvement.
n.o: Federal cost limit: $15 million per project (increased by WRDA 2024). Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal.

n.d: CAP for clearing and snagging channels for navigation and flood control purposes.
n.s: Flood Control Act of 1954, Section 208; 33 U.S.C. § 701g
n.o: Federal cost limit: $500,000 per project. Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal.

n.d: CAP for modifying existing Corps projects to improve environmental quality.
a: Project Modifications for Improvement of the Environment
n.o: Federal cost limit: $15 million per project (increased by WRDA 2024). Cost share: 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal.

n.d: New CAP established by WRDA 2024 for stormwater management projects to control, retain, and reuse stormwater associated with flood control efforts.
Program providing study and design assistance to Indian tribes for water resources projects on tribal lands.
n.o: Made permanent by WRDA 2024 Section 1140. Cost share may be reduced based on ability to pay.

n.d: State and regional authorities for USACE assistance with water supply, wastewater, and stormwater infrastructure.
n.o: Cost share is typically 75% Federal / 25% non-Federal, with provisions for economically disadvantaged communities.

n.d: General environmental infrastructure authority providing assistance for water and wastewater projects in specified areas.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1304 added numerous new project locations under Section 219.

n.d: Environmental infrastructure authority for the State of Pennsylvania (expanded from South Central Pennsylvania by WRDA 2024).
Environmental infrastructure authority for Southern West Virginia counties.
Environmental infrastructure authority for Northern West Virginia counties.
Environmental infrastructure authority for Ohio and North Dakota.
a: Ohio and North Dakota Environmental Infrastructure

n.d: Environmental infrastructure authority for rural communities in western states.
Program providing planning assistance to states for comprehensive water resources planning.
n.o: Cost share: 50% Federal / 50% non-Federal. WRDA 2024 Section 1127 added title research for abandoned structures.

n.d: Program providing technical assistance and information for floodplain management.
n.o: Services provided at 100% Federal cost.

n.d: Interagency flood risk management program facilitating collaboration between Federal, state, and local agencies.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1114 directs continuation of the program.

n.d: Program for restoration and enhancement of Great Lakes and connecting channels.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1363 added additional locations to the program.

n.d: Authority to conduct watershed and river basin assessments for water resources development opportunities.
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1143 added Walla Walla River Basin and San Francisco Bay Basin as priority areas.

n.d: Authority for control of aquatic plant growths and invasive species.
n.s: River and Harbor Act of 1958, Section 104; WRDA 2024 Section 1144
n.o: WRDA 2024 Section 1144 added Connecticut River Basin to the program.

n.d: Authority for rehabilitation of dams originally constructed by USACE that require significant repair or rehabilitation.
n.o: Extended through 2029 by WRDA 2024 Section 1367.

n.d: Parties with roles and responsibilities in Civil Works authorization, funding, and implementation.
Federal government entities with responsibilities in Civil Works authorization and implementation.
The statutory authority for Civil Works activities. Most WRDA provisions direct the 'Secretary' to take actions, meaning the Secretary of the Army acting through the Chief of Engineers.
n.o: In WRDA legislation, 'Secretary' always means the Secretary of the Army unless otherwise specified.

n.d: Senior military officer commanding the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, who signs Chief's Reports recommending project construction.

n.l: Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works
n.d: Civilian official responsible for policy direction and oversight of the Civil Works program.
U.S. Army Corps of Engineers organizational units responsible for Civil Works activities.
Headquarters of U.S. Army Corps of Engineers providing policy, guidance, and oversight.
Regional command level of USACE providing oversight of multiple districts. Eight Civil Works divisions cover the United States.
n.o: Civil Works Divisions: Great Lakes and Ohio River, Mississippi Valley, North Atlantic, Northwestern, Pacific Ocean, South Atlantic, South Pacific, Southwestern.

n.d: Field operating unit of USACE responsible for project execution. 38 districts conduct Civil Works activities.
Non-Federal entity that provides the non-Federal share of project costs and assumes responsibility for operation and maintenance of completed projects.

City, county, or other local governmental entity serving as non-Federal interest.
Federally recognized Indian tribal government serving as non-Federal interest.
Public entity responsible for port development and operations, often serving as non-Federal interest for navigation projects.
Special district responsible for levee construction, operation, and maintenance.
Special district responsible for water supply, irrigation, or related services.

Congressional agency conducting audits, evaluations, and studies of Federal programs including USACE Civil Works.

n.d: Structured allocation of project costs between Federal and non-Federal interests, varying by project purpose, phase, and applicable provisions.
n.o: Cost sharing requirements established by WRDA 1986 and modified by subsequent legislation. Explicit modeling enables computation and validation of cost shares.

Cost sharing during feasibility study phase.

n.d: Cost sharing during construction phase, varying by project purpose.

n.d: Standard cost sharing formulas based on project purpose/mission area.
Cost sharing for navigation projects, varying by depth and type.
Cost sharing for navigation channels greater than 14 feet deep.
n.o: Construction to 20': 80% Federal / 20% non-Federal. 20-45': 65% Federal / 35% non-Federal. 45-55' (increased from 50' by WRDA 2024): 50% Federal / 50% non-Federal. O&M: 100% Federal.

n.d: Cost sharing for navigation channels 14 feet or less.

Types of aquatic ecosystems and features subject to restoration.

The dynamic and interrelating complex of biotic communities and their associated nonliving environment, considered as an integrated unit. Implied within this definition are the concepts of structure and function. Ecosystem restoration is scalable and may encompass multiple states, more localized watersheds, or a smaller complex of aquatic habitats.

Ecosystem restoration improves degraded ecosystem structure and function to a less degraded, more natural condition. Restored ecosystems should mimic, as closely as possible, conditions that would occur in the area in the absence of human changes to the landscape and hydrology. The goal is to partially or fully reestablish the attributes of a naturalistic, functioning, and self-regulating system.

Structure refers to the composition of the ecosystem in terms of its various parts and the physical and biological organization defining how those parts are organized. Ecosystem function is the process that takes place in an ecosystem through the interactions of the plants, animals, and other organisms in the ecosystem with each other or their environment. Ecosystem structure and function provide various ecosystem goods and services of value to humans such as fish for recreational or commercial use, clean water to swim in or drink, and various esthetic qualities.
The manipulation of the physical, chemical, or biological characteristics of a habitat to change a specific function or seral stage of the habitat.
A type of restoration that prevents the loss of habitat.
n.o: Protection measures are most appropriate if they require USACE engineering expertise in accomplishing the measure.

n.d: Mitigation consists of those measures taken to avoid, minimize, rectify, reduce, or compensate for adverse environmental impacts. Compensatory mitigation measures are designed to replace ecological resources unavoidably affected by a USACE project or activity.
n.o: Ecosystem restoration projects should be designed to avoid the need for fish and wildlife mitigation. Projects implemented using ecosystem restoration authorities may not be used as wetland banks or mitigation credit for other entities.

n.d: In the context of USACE programs and missions, 'environmental restoration' is more commonly associated with 'cleanup' measures undertaken to achieve compliance with state and/or federal laws or regulations to clean up hazardous, toxic, and radioactive wastes. It generally refers to actions such as CERCLA remedial actions, RCRA corrective actions, and cleanups related to underground storage tanks.
n.o: Care should be taken in the use of this term, which is often inappropriately used interchangeably with 'ecosystem restoration.'

n.d: A specific type of action that may be recommended to restore aquatic ecosystems.
Use of dredged material to restore wetlands.
Restoring floodplain function by reconnecting floodplains, oxbows, and riparian wetlands to the main river channel.
Providing for more natural river corridor conditions needed to support ecosystem structure and function including restoration of riparian vegetation and sediment transport.
Modifying obstructions to fish passage, including dam removal.
Modifying dams and their operations to improve dissolved oxygen levels or temperature downstream or to improve sediment transport.
Removal of drainage structures and levees to restore wetland hydrology.
Restoring conditions conducive to native aquatic and riparian vegetation. This may include the removal of invasive species.

Generally refers to a buffer area adjacent to an aquatic site. This may include portions of a floodplain that infrequently flood, other riparian areas, or uplands adjacent to aquatic sites. Buffers are important as wildlife corridors, habitat for terrestrial and avian species, and in providing vegetation that reduces sedimentation and that may provide shade or other functions that support a healthy system.
n.o: Aquatic ecosystem restoration projects may include terrestrial buffer areas of limited width, if supported by the specific project objectives and scientific research.

n.d: The primary authorizing legislation for the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers. This comprehensive legislative package is typically passed every two years and may include both Congressional policy direction and authorization for USACE water resources activities including studies, projects, programs, and research activities.

Section 1135 of WRDA 1986, as amended, provides continuing authority to modify structures and operations of Civil Works projects to improve the environment to the extent the original authorized purposes are not adversely affected.

Section 204 of WRDA 1992, as amended, provides beneficial use authority for USACE to restore, protect, and create aquatic and wetland habitats in connection with construction or maintenance dredging of an authorized project.

Section 206 of PL 104-303, as amended, provides continuing authority for aquatic ecosystem restoration and protection for projects that improve the quality of the environment consistent with the public interest and that are found to be cost-effective.

Section 216 of the River and Harbor and Flood Control Act of 1970, as amended, allows the evaluation of the impact of constructed Civil Works projects on the environment and for the review of project operations and to recommend modifications to improve the quality of the environment.

Section 22 of WRDA 1974, as amended, created the Planning Assistance to States program authorizing cooperation with States, Tribes, and Territories in preparation of comprehensive plans for development, utilization, and conservation of water and related land resources.
Federal law with objective to restore and maintain the chemical, physical, and biological integrity of the Nation's waters.

n.d: Federal law requiring coordination with resource agencies on projects affecting fish and wildlife.

The structured planning process defined in the Economic and Environmental Principles and Guidelines for Water and Land Related Resources Implementation Studies (P&G) as applied to ecosystem restoration.

First planning step where problems and opportunities are defined in terms of their nature, cause, location, dimensions, origin, time frame, and importance. Includes development of objectives and constraints.

Second planning step where both existing conditions and future conditions expected to occur without a project are characterized. The future without-project condition forms the basis from which alternative plans are formulated.

Third planning step consisting of identifying management measures, preliminary screening, developing plan formulation strategies, formulating alternatives by combining compatible measures, and iterative reformulation.
Fourth planning step where plan effects are evaluated using cost effectiveness and incremental cost analysis (CE/ICA), documenting significance of ecosystem outputs, and evaluating P&G criteria.
Fifth planning step where alternative plans are compared against each other to identify the recommended plan through comparison of effects and documentation of tradeoffs.

Sixth planning step where a single alternative plan is selected for recommendation based on all evaluation criteria including cost effectiveness, significance, acceptability, completeness, efficiency, and effectiveness.
A clearly defined statement of the ecosystem degradation problem to be addressed, including nature, cause, location, dimensions, origin, time frame, and importance.

Specific, flexible, measurable, realistic, attainable, and acceptable objectives developed based on study area problems and opportunities. Should include subject, effect, location, timing, and duration.
Actions or outcomes to avoid in developing plans aimed at meeting study objectives and addressing problems and opportunities.
A feature or activity that can be implemented at a specific geographic site to address one or more restoration planning objectives.
A feature or activity, that can be implemented at a specific geographic site to address one or more restoration planning objectives.
A feature is a part of an alternative plan that requires construction or assembly on-site in the project area.

A qualitative representation of ecosystem processes and characteristics (structure, functions, and services) that explains how ecological conditions related to identified problems are expected to change under future conditions and how measures would alter future ecological processes.
n.o: Conceptual models are qualitative, may be graphical and/or narrative, and do not require certification.

n.d: The future conditions expected to occur without implementation of a project. Forms the basis from which alternative plans are formulated and impacts are assessed over the period of analysis.
The time period over which alternative plans are evaluated. May be up to 50 years for most projects or up to 100 years for major multiple purpose reservoir projects with prior approval.

Ecosystem restoration planning and management that is watershed in scale using systems analysis methods and tools to understand, assess, and model the interconnected nature of hydrologic systems and the economic and ecologic systems they support.

Analysis to show that an alternative restoration plan's output cannot be produced more cost effectively by another alternative. Cost effective means that for a given level of non-monetary output, no other plan costs less, and no other plan yields more output for less money.

Analysis where a variety of implementable alternatives and various-sized alternatives are evaluated to arrive at a 'best' level of output. Examines cost-effective plans sequentially by increasing scale to identify plans most efficient in production of ecosystem benefits.
Combined cost effectiveness and incremental cost analysis used in evaluation of alternative ecosystem restoration plans.
a: Cost Effectiveness and Incremental Cost Analysis

n.d: A plan where for a particular level of output, no other plan costs less and no plan yields more output for the same or less cost.

A cost-effective plan that provides the greatest increase in output for the least increase in cost. Has the lowest incremental costs per unit of output when compared with all other plans producing as much or more output.
The additional cost incurred in selecting one plan over another, or the difference in cost between each alternative and the no action alternative.
The additional output gained in selecting one plan over another, or the difference in output between each alternative and the no action alternative.
Costs derived from first calculating all costs in terms of present worth using the appropriate discount rate and then annualizing using the same discount rate.

A unit measuring the output of a restoration plan. Units are obtained by computing the difference between the baseline no action plan compared to the habitat improvement results of a restoration plan alternative. The outputs can be annualized for comparing outputs against costs.
The excess of monetary and non-monetary beneficial effects over monetary and non-monetary costs. The NER plan is where incremental beneficial effects just equal incremental costs.
The four evaluation criteria specified in the Economic and Environmental Principles and Guidelines: completeness, effectiveness, efficiency, and acceptability.

A plan must provide and account for all necessary investments or other actions needed to ensure the realization of the planned restoration outputs. A plan does not need to fully satisfy every planning objective or include all parts of a study area to be complete.

An ecosystem restoration plan must make a significant contribution towards addressing the specified restoration problems or opportunities. A plan does not need to fully satisfy every planning objective to still be considered effective.

An ecosystem restoration plan must represent a cost-effective means of addressing the restoration problem or opportunity. It must be determined that the plan's restoration outputs cannot be produced more cost effectively by another alternative.

The extent to which alternative ecosystem restoration plans are acceptable in terms of applicable laws, regulations, and public policies. Support from resource agencies, local governments, the non-federal sponsor, and the public should be considered.
Categories for displaying plan effects as specified in the Principles and Guidelines.
The National Economic Development account displays changes in the economic value of the national output of goods and services.
The Environmental Quality account displays effects on significant natural and cultural resources.
The Regional Economic Development account displays the regional and localized economic impacts that result from each alternative plan.
The Other Social Effects account registers plan effects from perspectives that are relevant to the planning process but are not reflected in the NED, NER, or EQ accounts.

The alternative having the maximum excess of monetary and non-monetary beneficial effects over monetary and non-monetary costs. This plan occurs where the incremental beneficial effects just equal the incremental costs.
n.o: Deviations from the NER plan require justification and the granting of an exception from the ASA(CW).

n.d: A plan that is supported by the non-Federal partner that is different from the NED, NER, or total net benefits plan.

For plans formulated to produce both economic and restoration benefits, the plan with the greatest economic and restoration benefits relative to the costs is to be selected, consistent with protecting the Nation's environment, unless the ASA(CW) grants an exception.
The baseline alternative representing conditions without implementation of any project, used as the basis for comparison with action alternatives.

Qualitative information to help decision-makers evaluate whether the value of the resources of any given alternative are worth the costs incurred to produce them. Recognized in terms of institutional, public, and/or technical importance.

The recognition of ecosystem restoration project outputs in terms of institutional, public, and technical importance. Collectively this assessment helps decision makers in the 'is it worth it' aspect of recommending a plan.

Significance based on institutional recognition means that the importance of an environmental resource is acknowledged in the laws, adopted plans, and other policy statements of public agencies, Tribes, or private groups.

Public recognition means that some segment of the public recognizes the importance of an environmental resource, as evidenced by people engaged in activities that reflect an interest or concern for a particular resource.

Tribes and Indigenous Peoples hold relevant information and perspectives regarding the environment, and Indigenous Knowledge can inform recognition of resource significance and other planning analysis.
Technical recognition means that a resource qualifies as significant based on its 'technical' merits, which are based on scientific knowledge or assessment of critical resource characteristics.

A measure of a resource's relative abundance within a specified geographic range. Generally, a habitat or ecosystem is considered rare if it occupies a narrow geographic range or occurs in small groupings.

A measure of a resource's ability to exemplify the natural habitat or ecosystems within a specified range. The presence of a large number and percentage of native species, and the absence of exotic species, implies representativeness.

Evaluating the occurrence and extent of the resource over time, how it has changed, and why. Documenting the status or health of the resource includes describing its physical attributes, the extent of degradation, and any human alterations.
A measure of the potential for movement and dispersal of species throughout an area or ecosystem. Should be considered in the context of an entire landscape or watershed.
Habitat that is essential for the conservation, survival, or recovery of one or more species. May be both institutionally and technically significant.

The specific areas within the geographic area, occupied by the species at the time it was listed, that contain the physical or biological features that are essential to the conservation of endangered and threatened species and that may need special management or protection.
n.o: Since the term 'critical habitat' has specific legal and regulatory ramifications, it should only be used in relation to federally listed species.

n.d: A measure of the variety of distinct species and the genetic variability within them. Can be measured at the individual level (genetic variation), population level (species variation), and the community level (variation of biological communities and interaction of ecosystem functions).

A body of observations, oral and written knowledge, practices, and beliefs that promote environmental sustainability and the responsible stewardship of natural resources through relationships between humans and environmental systems. Applied to phenomena across biological, physical, cultural, and spiritual systems.

A formal, science-based approach to risk management that permits implementation of actions despite uncertainties. Knowledge gained from monitoring and evaluating results is used to adjust and direct future decisions.

A plan included in the final decision document for systematic collection and analysis of data that provides information useful for assessing project performance and determining whether ecological restoration success has been achieved.

A plan developed for each ecosystem restoration project describing the nature and cost of actions that may be needed to modify project elements because of high uncertainty in achieving intended results, as well as the triggers to implement each adaptive management action.

A determination that the physical and/or biological developments of the restoration project have progressed on a trajectory and at a rate sufficient to assure that the restoration objectives will be reached within an acceptable timeframe.

Measurable indicators of ecological success developed to address project objectives and link to monitoring and adaptive management plans. May include structural characteristics, processes, or biodiversity.

A determination made by the Division Commander that ecological restoration success has been achieved, based on monitoring results documented by the District Engineer in consultation with federal and state resource agencies.

Required monitoring for a period not to exceed ten years funded and cost shared as a project cost. Monitoring periods of less than ten years are allowed if sufficient to make a determination of ecological restoration success.

Management actions undertaken to achieve an outcome or a natural feature created to contribute to ecosystem restoration objectives. Examples include planting native vegetation, removing invasive species, establishing oyster reefs or living shorelines, placing dredged material to create marsh, dredging to reconnect channels and floodplains, or placement of large woody debris.
n.o: O&M of nonstructural and nonmechanical elements ceases 10 years after ecological success is determined.

The Federal objective in ecosystem restoration planning is to contribute to national ecosystem restoration. Contributions are increases in the net quantity and/or quality of desired improvements of structure, function, and services of ecosystem resources.

An exception granted by the Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works allowing deviation from standard policy, such as recommending a plan other than the NER plan.

A measure to increase and enhance floodplains by moving levees back from the river channel, encouraged in aquatic ecosystem restoration projects as it supports community resilience and ecosystem benefits.

National policy to maximize beneficial use of dredged material in an environmentally acceptable manner, obtained from the construction or operation and maintenance of water resources development projects.
A study conducted under USACE aquatic ecosystem restoration authorities to develop and evaluate alternative plans for restoring degraded ecosystem structure and function.
A study to determine feasibility of ecosystem restoration projects, with costs shared 50/50 with non-federal sponsor.
A study of river basins and regions that may identify ecosystem restoration needs and lead to detailed feasibility studies.
A study conducted under one of the USACE continuing authorities that include ecosystem restoration (Section 1135, 204, 206).
A combination of restoration measures and features designed to restore degraded ecosystem structure and function.
The plan where incremental beneficial effects just equal incremental costs - the recommended plan unless an exception is granted by ASA(CW).
Plans identified through CE/ICA as having the lowest incremental costs per unit of output compared to all other plans producing as much or more output.

A study that results in a feasibility report under section 2282 of this title, and any associated environmental impact statement and mitigation plan, prepared by the Corps of Engineers for a water resources project.
n.o: Defined in 33 USC 2215(d)(2). The term includes a study that results in a general reevaluation report. May result in no Federal interest and no recommendation (study termination).

n.d: A determination that establishes the Federal interest in carrying out the study and the projects that may be proposed in the study.
n.o: Based upon the existence of at least one alternative that contributes to the Federal Objective and Guiding Principles. Must be completed within 120 days. Cost limited to $300,000 at full Federal expense.

n.d: Federally authorized feasibility studies of proposed water resources development projects undertaken by a non-Federal interest for submission to the ASA(CW).
n.o: Authorized under Section 203 of WRDA 1986, as amended (33 USC 2231).

n.d: Continuing Authorities Program studies that convert to Investigations program funded studies.
n.o: Considered new start feasibility studies because they have never received Investigations funding. Requires specific study authority.

n.d: A study performed for a project where construction was never initiated or during construction but prior to the completion of construction.

A study performed on an authorized project prior to initiation of construction or prior to construction completion that investigates potential changes to authorized projects that would modify authorized outputs, add a project purpose, significantly change the authorized plan, or otherwise involve the formulation of new or modified solutions.
n.o: Involves reformulation of alternatives from a previously completed feasibility study. Cost shared 50/50 Federal/non-Federal from Investigations account under FCSA.

n.d: A study used prior to construction completion of an authorized project that is limited in scope compared to a general reevaluation study.
n.o: May address economic justification, environmental effects, impacts of revised policy and minor project formulation. Use should be rare. Cost shared 50/50.

n.d: A study developed to affirm project justification through updates to cost, benefits, or other economic and/or environmental impacts, which does not require formulation of new or modified alternatives.
n.o: Performed prior to construction completion. May use any funds appropriated for current project phase. Approved by Division Commander except for Section 902 cases.

n.d: A type of validation study conducted when the construction of an authorized project cannot be completed within the maximum total project cost allowed by Section 902 of WRDA 1986, as amended.
n.o: Results in a Section 902 post-authorization change report. Reviewed and approved at HQUSACE.

n.d: A study to evaluate extension of Federal participation in beach renourishment beyond the originally authorized period.
n.o: May extend participation up to 50 years after initial construction without Congressional action (42 USC 1962d-5f(a)), or study extension beyond 50 years requiring additional authorization.

n.d: A study under the general authority to review completed projects in the interest of navigation, flood risk management, water supply and related purposes if found advisable due to significantly changed physical or economic conditions, and for improving the quality of the environment in the overall public interest.
n.o: Requires initial appraisal report (limited to $20,000, federally funded with O&M funds). Excludes design or construction deficiencies.

n.d: A specific type of study conducted under the authority of Section 216 of the Flood Control Act of 1970 or other specific authorities with the intent to determine whether an authorized water resources development project should be deauthorized and if the associated real property and Government-owned improvements should undergo disposal.
n.o: 100% Federally funded under Investigations account. Does not require new start budget decision.

n.d: A study to determine whether to pursue a dam safety modification study by focusing on all significant potential failure modes when evaluating risk, verify the current dam safety action classification, and guide the selection and gauge the effectiveness of interim risk reduction measures.
A study to identify and recommend a risk management plan that supports the expeditious and cost-effective reduction of risk within the overall USACE portfolio of dams.
n.o: Recommended alternatives must be technically feasible and acceptable following current best practices.

n.d: A study limited to addressing impediments that prevent a project from performing as authorized after all maintenance has been accomplished and any deficiencies resulting from lack of maintenance have been addressed.
n.o: Design or construction deficiency is a flaw that significantly interferes with project's authorized purposes. Falls within original project authority.

n.d: A study-like activity for projects that involve replacing or recapitalizing the principal facility features to enable production of project benefits.
n.o: Should show significantly improved reliability and extended physical life, deferring capital expenditure to replace structure. Does not include major maintenance, routine, or deferred maintenance.

n.d: A study whose scope reflects the level of detail necessary to meet the provisions of the specific study authority, addressing problems, needs, and opportunities within the basin.
n.o: Will not produce a recommendation for authorization of a water resources development project but may result in recommendations for more detailed feasibility studies.

n.d: A feasibility study specifically identified in a final report from a comprehensive or basin-wide study that would be carried out under the same study authority as the comprehensive or basin-wide study.
A study of water needs of river basins and watersheds of the United States in consultation with Tribal, state, interstate, and local governmental entities.
n.o: Authorized under Section 729 of WRDA 1986, as amended. Cost shared 75% Federal / 25% non-Federal.

n.d: Water-related planning activities and activities that relate to the study, design, and construction of water resources development projects that will substantially benefit Indian tribes.
n.o: Located primarily within Indian country or in proximity to Alaska Native villages.

n.l: Shoreline and Riverine Protection and Restoration Study
n.d: Studies to reduce flood and hurricane and storm damage hazards or restore natural functions and values of rivers and shorelines, emphasizing natural and nature-based features including nonstructural approaches.
n.o: Maximum Federal cost to design and construct is $15 million without further Congressional authorization.

n.d: A document that presents study findings and recommendations for approval and/or Congressional authorization.
A decision document supported by the feasibility study that requires Congressional authorization for the Secretary of the Army to carry out a project.
n.o: Can include projects in which additional authorization due to a significant change to an existing authorization is proposed.

n.d: A decision document supported by a validation study that provides a recommendation for a change to a project that may need further Congressional authorization as the recommendation made exceeds the Chief's discretionary authority under existing law.

A decision or implementation document supported by a validation study or limited reevaluation study that provides a recommendation for projects or project modifications within the existing authorization and does not need Congressional authorization or supports a budgetary request.
Documentation produced as the output of a planning study.

A report that describes, with reasonable certainty, the economic, environmental, and social benefits and detriments of the recommended plan and alternative plans considered, as well as the engineering features, the public acceptability, and the purposes, scope, and scale of the recommended plan.
n.o: Must include views of other Federal agencies and non-Federal agencies regarding the recommended plan.

n.d: A report resulting from a general reevaluation study, developed to feasibility study scope and level of detail.
A report resulting from a limited reevaluation study.
A report documenting validation study findings including changes to cost, benefits, or other economic and/or environmental impacts.
A report resulting from a Section 902 post-authorization study process addressing cost increases exceeding authorized limits.
A report for Section 216 studies that determines whether there is a Federal interest in undertaking a study to consider modifications to a completed project.
n.o: Cost limited to $20,000, federally funded with O&M funds. Intent is to demonstrate significant change in physical or economic conditions since project completion, or possibility of improving environmental quality.

n.d: A report that revalidates and reaffirms an existing beach renourishment project, including cost update, design template reaffirmation, real estate validation, and environmental compliance review.
A report resulting from a watershed assessment study.
A report resulting from a dam safety modification study, approved by HQ Dam Safety Officer.
A report for major rehabilitation projects showing significantly improved reliability and extended physical life of existing structures.
A document supporting project implementation that is not a decision document.
A record of final design effort after the feasibility phase that provides the technical basis for plans and specifications and serves as a summary of final design.
n.o: Required for all engineering design products.

n.d: A report that may be used in lieu of a general reevaluation report to document technical changes when project reformulation is not required.
n.o: May also be prepared for individual projects authorized as part of a large system study. Approval level is at District command.

n.d: A long-term strategy for providing viable placement alternatives that meet the dredging needs of Federal navigation channels and includes consideration of state and local dredging needs.
n.o: Identifies, evaluates, screens, prioritizes, and optimizes placement alternatives for at least the next 20 years. Approved by Division Commander.

n.d: The organizational level authorized to approve a planning report or decision document.
Approval authority reserved for the Assistant Secretary of the Army for Civil Works.

n.d: Approval authority reserved by the USACE Chief of Engineers for planning reports documenting changes to authorized projects not meeting delegation criteria and not requiring Congressional authorization.
Approval authority at HQUSACE by the Director of Civil Works for reports meeting specific criteria including pre-May 2018 draft release, policy exceptions required, or vertical team recommendation.
Delegated approval authority for planning reports when changes to authorized projects meet all specified criteria.
n.o: Cannot be further delegated. Criteria include: cost increase no greater than price level changes, scope change no greater than 20%, minor location/design changes, no addition/deletion of project purpose.

n.d: Approval authority at the District level for specific documents such as Engineering Documentation Reports.
Approval authority for Dam Safety Modification Reports.
A major phase in the lifecycle of a USACE project relative to Congressional authorization and construction status.
Activities that occur before a project is specifically authorized by Congress for construction.

Activities that occur after a project is specifically authorized by Congress for construction but are performed for the authorized project prior to initiation of construction or prior to construction completion.
The phase during which detailed design and construction activities occur.
The phase after construction completion when the project is operated and maintained.
The division of costs between Federal and non-Federal interests for studies and projects.
Cost sharing arrangement with 50 percent Federal and 50 percent non-Federal funds.
n.o: Standard for feasibility studies, general reevaluation studies, limited reevaluation studies, and beach renourishment evaluation studies.

n.d: Cost sharing arrangement with 75 percent Federal and 25 percent non-Federal funds.
n.o: Used for watershed assessments under Section 729 of WRDA 1986.

n.d: Cost sharing arrangement with 90 percent Federal and 10 percent non-Federal funds for economically disadvantaged communities.
n.o: Applies to design and construction for shoreline and riverine protection under Section 212 of WRDA 1999.

n.d: Activities funded entirely by Federal funds with no non-Federal cost share required.
n.o: Applies to Federal interest determinations (up to $300,000), initial appraisal reports ($20,000), disposition studies, and first $200,000 of shoreline/riverine studies.

n.d: Minimum non-Federal cost share for design and construction established in 33 USC 2213.
Statutory provisions that authorize USACE studies, projects, and programs.
Legislative authority that authorizes USACE to conduct specific planning studies.
Authority provided through specific provisions in Water Resources Development Acts and other acts submitted by Congress and enacted by the President.
n.o: Previously, study resolutions were passed by the Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works and the House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure.

n.d: A standing authority that allows USACE to plan and implement projects of limited size, cost, scope, and complexity without requiring study or project-specific authority.
n.o: Each continuing authority has specific legislative authority and per-project and program Federal cost limits.

n.d: Review of navigation, flood control, and water supply projects - provides general study authority to review completed projects.
a: Section 216 of Flood Control Act of 1970

n.d: Flood control and other purposes - establishes cost sharing requirements.
Feasibility studies; planning, engineering, and design.
Study of water resources development projects by non-Federal interests.
Watershed and river basin assessments.
Tribal partnership program.
Maximum cost of projects - limits increases in total project cost to 20 percent for projects authorized after 17 November 1986.
Feasibility reports - requirements for feasibility study content.
Vertical integration and acceleration of studies.
Annual report to Congress on Future Water Resources Development.
Shoreline and riverine protection and restoration.
Water resources development projects involving navigation, flood control, and shore protection - provides procedure for authorization of projects under $15 million Federal cost.
a: Section 201 of Flood Control Act of 1965

n.d: Beach nourishment - authorizes extension of Federal participation.
Development of water supplies for domestic, municipal, industrial, and other purposes.
A congressionally authorized purpose for a Civil Works project.
Project purpose for maintaining navigable waterways.
Project purpose for reducing flood damages.
Project purpose for providing water for domestic, municipal, industrial, and other uses.
n.o: May be added without Congressional approval under Water Supply Act of 1958 (43 USC 390b) if modification does not seriously affect authorized purposes.

n.d: Project purpose for regulation of stream flow to improve water quality.
n.o: No general authority available for adding water quality as a purpose. Deletion procedures established in 33 USC 1252a.

n.d: Project purpose for recreational use of project facilities and lands.
n.o: Governed by Federal Water Project Recreation Act (16 USC 460l-12 through 16 USC 460l-21).

n.d: Project purpose for enhancement of fish and wildlife resources.
Project purpose for restoration of aquatic ecosystems.
Project purpose for generation of hydroelectric power.
n.o: Provision for future hydroelectric power at authorized dams requires Chief of Engineers and FERC recommendations with ASA(CW) approval (33 USC 701j).

n.d: Project purpose for protection of shorelines from erosion and storm damage.
Project purpose for stream flow regulation for purposes other than water quality.
n.o: Can be added if Chief of Engineers determines feasible. Reports recommending deletion must be processed to Congress for authorization.

A group of nine legislative authorities funded in the Construction appropriation that authorize the ASA(CW), acting through the Chief of Engineers, to plan, design, and implement certain types of water resources projects without additional, project-specific Congressional authorization.

Program authorizing USACE, in cooperation with Indian tribes and Alaska Native tribal governments, to carry out water-related planning activities and water resources development projects that substantially benefit Indian tribes.
Program providing technical services and planning guidance to state, regional, Tribal, territorial, and local governments without charge.
n.o: Authorized by Section 206 of the Flood Control Act of 1960, as amended (33 USC 709a). Assistance may be provided to Federal agencies and private persons on cost recovery or fee basis.

n.d: Program authorizing technical assistance pertaining to planning for water and related resources through comprehensive plans and technical assistance.
Organizations and roles involved in USACE planning processes.

A legally constituted public body (including an Indian tribe and a tribal organization); or a nonprofit entity with consent of the affected local government, that has full authority and capability to perform agreement terms and pay damages if necessary.
n.o: Partner in entire study process and treated as full member of project delivery team.

Liaisons between Districts, Divisions and HQUSACE that ensure flow of information and products and provide guidance where appropriate.
The chain of review and decision-making spanning District, Division, and HQUSACE levels.
Formal agreements between USACE and non-Federal interests governing cost sharing and responsibilities.

A legally binding agreement that specifies the percentage and amount of funding the Federal government and a non-Federal interest will both contribute to a feasibility study, processes to be followed, and roles and responsibilities of both parties.
Agreement governing cost sharing during preconstruction engineering and design phase.
Agreement governing cost sharing and responsibilities during project construction and implementation.
Concepts related to the planning study process and decision-making.
Planning approach that uses risk-informed techniques to manage risks and make uncertainty transparent by gathering only the evidence needed to make the next planning decision.
n.o: All studies and reports utilize risk-informed decision-making principles. All decision meetings framed around these principles.

n.d: Decision meeting where approval of the Federal interest determination occurs.
n.o: Decision-maker is MSC Planning & Policy Chief. Affirms PDT's preliminary analysis of federal interest and projected scope, schedule, and budget for the study. Expected within 90-180 days of study start.

n.d: A decision point for initiating new studies or study phases that does not constitute a new start.
Category for studies that are new investment decisions but not new starts.
A new feasibility study that has not previously received Investigations funding.
Process of developing new or modified alternatives from a previously completed feasibility study.
n.o: If reformulation is required during PED, districts prepare general reevaluation report or limited reevaluation report. If required during validation study, converts to general reevaluation study.

n.d: Types of changes to authorized projects and their authorization requirements.
Changes in the general level of money prices in the economy, or in sectors of the economy, measured by appropriate price indices or observation of changes in particular unit prices.
Increases or decreases in the outputs for the authorized purposes of a project resulting from formulation or design changes.

n.o: Not considered changes in scope.

n.d: Changes to authorized projects that always require Congressional authorization.
n.o: Includes: adding/deleting project purpose, certain fish/wildlife mitigation acquisitions, changes to local cooperation requirements in authorizing language, navigation channel deepening, and cost increases over 20% for post-1986 projects.

n.d: Economic analysis concepts used in planning studies.
The ratio between the discounted present value of benefits and the discounted present value of costs.

n.d: Allocation of project costs among project purposes.
Division of Federal and non-Federal costs for a project.

Document that determines whether or not a Federal action has the potential to cause significant environmental effects.
Document prepared if a proposed major Federal action is determined to significantly affect the quality of the human environment.
Category of actions that do not individually or cumulatively have significant environmental effects and are excluded from NEPA documentation requirements.
USACE Engineer Regulations, Pamphlets, and Manuals referenced in planning guidance.
