A project for which construction has been completed.
An authorized project where construction was never initiated or is not yet complete.
A community meeting the definition established by ASA(CW) memorandum dated 14 March 2023, qualifying for reduced non-Federal cost share.
Concepts related to deauthorization and disposal of USACE projects.
Any authorized method of permanently divesting the Department of Army of control of and responsibility for real estate.
Congressional action to remove the authorization for a water resources development project.
n.o: Property or improvements required for project function cannot be disposed of until Congress deauthorizes the project.

n.d: One of nine legislative authorities under the Continuing Authorities Program authorizing specific types of water resources projects without additional project-specific Congressional authorization.

CAP authority for implementing projects to protect public facilities and facilities owned by non-profit organizations that are used to provide public services, from natural erosion processes on stream banks and shorelines.
a: Emergency Streambank and Shoreline Erosion Protection
n.o: Per-project limit: $5,000,000. Annual program limit: $25,000,000. Eligible facilities include highways, bridge approaches, public works, churches, hospitals, schools, and historic properties. Cost sharing follows structural FRM requirements (35-50% non-Federal).

n.d: CAP authority for protecting multiple public and private properties and facilities and single non-Federal public properties and facilities against damages caused by storm driven waves and currents.
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $37,500,000. Cost sharing follows CSRM requirements (35% non-Federal for CSRM purpose, 100% non-Federal for privately owned shores with limited use).

n.d: CAP authority for commercial and recreational navigation improvement projects.
a: Small River and Harbor Improvement Projects
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $62,500,000. Commercial navigation cost sharing: 10% for depths ≤20 ft, 25% for depths 20-50 ft, 50% for depths >50 ft. Recreational navigation: 50% non-Federal. O&M of general navigation features is Federal responsibility.

n.d: CAP authority for prevention or mitigation of damages to both non-Federal public and privately owned shores to the extent such damages can be directly identified and attributed to Federal navigation works.
n.o: Per-project limit: $12,500,000. No annual program limit. Cost sharing follows the same proportion as the Federal navigation project causing the shore damage. Geographic limitation: extends only to damages attributable to the navigation project.

n.d: CAP authority for beneficial use of sediment obtained from construction, operation, and maintenance of authorized projects for purposes including storm damage reduction, habitat restoration and creation, and sediment transport.
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $62,500,000. Feasibility phase is 100% Federally funded. Sediment may come from Federal sources, other Federal agency sources, or non-Federal sources (not at Federal expense).

n.d: CAP authority for flood risk management projects of limited size, cost, scope, and complexity.
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $68,500,000. Cost sharing follows structural FRM requirements (35-50% non-Federal, minimum 5% cash). Type I IEPR exclusions require MSC Commander case-by-case approval.

n.d: CAP authority for aquatic ecosystem restoration projects.
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $62,500,000. A non-profit entity may serve as sole sponsor. Land values generally should not exceed 25% of total project costs. Requires monitoring plan and adaptive management plan.

n.d: CAP authority for snagging and clearing activities for flood risk management purposes.
a: Snagging and Clearing for Flood Control
Snagging and Clearing for Flood Risk Management
n.o: Per-project limit: $500,000. Annual program limit: $7,500,000. Limited to removal of accumulated snags and other debris and clearing and straightening of stream channels. Recreation features may not be added.

n.d: CAP authority for modifications to existing USACE projects to improve the quality of the environment when such modifications are determined to be feasible and consistent with the authorized project purposes.
a: Project Modifications for Improvement of Environment
n.o: Per-project limit: $10,000,000. Annual program limit: $50,000,000. A non-profit entity may serve as sole sponsor. 100% of non-Federal share may be performed as in-kind work. Requires monitoring plan and adaptive management plan.

n.d: Initial phase using Coordination Account funds for all initial contacts with potential sponsors, maintaining the CAP Database, creation of P2 projects, and initial actions required for project requests.
n.o: Funds are not cost shared and count against annual program limit but not per-project limit. Not to be used as supplements for other coordination activities with line item funding.

n.d: The project formulation phase during which all planning activities are performed that are required to demonstrate Federal participation in a specific CAP project is warranted, culminating in approval of the decision document.
n.o: Initially Federally funded up to $100,000 (except Section 204 at 100% Federal, Section 111 cost shared per navigation project). Remaining costs shared 50/50. Expected duration 1-2 years from FCSA execution.

n.d: The phase of a CAP project during which post-feasibility phase activities are performed including negotiation and execution of the PPA, final design, preparation of plans and specifications, construction, monitoring, adaptive management, and closeout.
n.o: All costs shared per authorizing legislation. PPA execution expected within 6 months of approved decision document.

n.d: The MSC approval memo used to verify that a CAP project potentially meets the requirements of Federal Interest and Corps responsibility as set forth in one of the CAP Authorities.
n.o: Prepared by the district using existing data, must be accomplished within $50,000 and prior to receipt of additional funding. Not considered a decision document. Must be completed within 4 months of receipt of funding.

n.d: The consolidated documentation of feasibility, technical and policy analyses, findings, and conclusions upon which the District Commander bases the recommendation to the MSC Commander to approve the recommended CAP project for implementation.
n.o: Approved by MSC Commander (cannot be delegated to District). Supports the Project Partnership Agreement.

n.d: Report transmitted by District Commander to MSC containing project description, final Federal and non-Federal feasibility and design and implementation costs by phase, and date of physical completion notice.
Agreement executed by District Commander and non-Federal sponsor for feasibility phase costs in excess of $100,000 for CAP projects.
n.o: Not required if feasibility phase can be completed for $100,000 or less, but is recommended. Not required for Section 204 (100% Federal feasibility). Authority follows CECW-P implementation memorandum dated May 19, 2016.

n.d: Agreement executed by District Commander and non-Federal sponsor governing the design and implementation phase of a CAP project.
n.o: Model PPAs must be used when available. HQ CAP manager determines which projects are authorized to execute a PPA during each fiscal year.

n.d: Process by which a CAP study is terminated and converted to an Investigations program funded study when the likely Federal cost of the solution exceeds the applicable Federal per-project limit.
n.o: Requires study authority to exist. MSC Commander approval required. CAP and Investigations funds may not be spent simultaneously. CAP expenditures do not count against CAP per-project or annual program limits after conversion.

n.d: Process by which an ongoing Investigations study or PED is transferred to CAP when determined to be a better fit under CAP.
n.o: MSC Commander approval required. Investigations phase must be terminated before CAP funds used. Investigations expenditures do not count against CAP per-project or annual program limits.

n.d: A legally constituted public body (including a federally recognized Indian tribe) serving as non-Federal sponsor for a CAP project.
n.o: Required for Sections 14, 103, 107, 111, 205, 208, and Section 204 with FRM or CSRM purpose. Must have full authority and capability to perform agreement terms.

n.d: A non-profit organization eligible to act as sole sponsor for CAP ecosystem restoration projects under Sections 204, 206, and 1135.
n.o: Must be incorporated as non-profit, exempt under IRC Section 501, with purposes related to project purpose. Requires consent of affected local government. Must demonstrate capability to satisfy sponsor responsibilities including OMRR&R in perpetuity.

n.d: The statutory maximum amount of Federal participation allowed for each specific project implemented under a CAP authority.
n.o: Includes all Corps CAP funds expended for feasibility and design and implementation activities. For Sections 204, 206, and 1135, includes expenditures by other Federal agencies. Federal funds in excess of limit may not be allotted even if NFI offers reimbursement.

n.d: The statutory maximum amount of Federal participation under a CAP authority in any one fiscal year.
n.o: For Sections 204, 206, and 1135, this is the limit on annual appropriations and obligations. For remaining authorities, this is the annual limit of allotments from HQUSACE. HQUSACE monitors limits and issues guidance if approached.

n.d: Planning, design, or implementation activities performed by the non-Federal sponsor in lieu of the Federal Government during the CAP feasibility or design and implementation phase.
n.o: Credit is limited so as not to result in reimbursement to NFI (except Section 1135 where 100% of non-Federal share may be in-kind). Value determined by audit for reasonableness, allowability, and allocability.

n.d: Funds above any statutorily required non-Federal cost share provided voluntarily by states, political subdivisions, or other non-Federal interests with no credit or repayment authorized.
n.o: May be accepted for further study, design, construction, and O&M after Federal funds have been provided to initiate study. Congressional notification required prior to acceptance.

n.d: CAP milestone held after alternative plans have been formulated and prior to release of the draft decision document for public review to ensure plans are properly formulated and MSC concurs with the tentatively selected plan.

Milestones used for notification and reporting purposes as required by 33 USC 2282(g), Detailed Project Schedule.
Product milestone marking the release of the draft feasibility report for public comment and concurrent review.

n.d: Product milestone marking the District Commander's transmittal of the final feasibility report to the MSC.
Product milestone marking the signature of the Chief's Report or Director's Report, completing the feasibility study.
Milestones marking confirmation and endorsement of key planning decisions made by the PDT during the feasibility study.

Decision milestone marking the PDT's recommendation of, and the decision-maker's endorsement of, a Tentatively Selected Plan (and LPP, if applicable), and that the PDT is prepared to release the draft feasibility report for concurrent review.
n.o: Decision-maker is MSC Planning & Policy Chief (or HQUSACE Chief of OWPR if decision-making retained at HQ). Expected within first 12 months of a 3-year study.

n.d: Decision milestone marking the corporate endorsement of the recommended plan and proposed way forward to complete feasibility-level design.
n.o: Decision-maker is MSC Programs Directorate Chief (SES), or HQUSACE Chief of Planning & Policy if decision-making retained at HQ. Occurs after completion of concurrent reviews of draft feasibility report.

Task to initiate Section 106 National Historic Preservation Act literature and records search and identification of the Area of Potential Effects.

Task to conduct at least one iteration of risk-informed planning process including developing problems, opportunities, objectives, and constraints; defining FWOP conditions; developing formulation strategies; formulating measures; combining measures into initial array of alternatives; and conducting preliminary screening.

Task to develop a PMP including draft Review Plan and communication strategy with specific details to achieve the TSP milestone and NEPA/NHPA compliance.
Task to use the pre-AMM study issue checklist to identify potential policy issues and conduct vertical coordination as needed.

Task to request Independent External Peer Review exclusion, if applicable.

Task to define Section 106 Area of Potential Effects and identify and evaluate historic properties within the APE.
Task to prepare draft conceptual mitigation proposals for environmental impacts.
Task to prepare Draft Biological Assessment for Endangered Species Act compliance, if applicable.
Task to prepare Essential Fish Habitat Assessment under Magnuson-Stevens Act, if applicable.
Task to seek Fish and Wildlife Coordination Act Report from USFWS and/or NMFS.
Task to develop draft Clean Water Act Section 404(b)(1) evaluation report.
Task to obtain habitat and other planning model approvals or certification, if applicable.
Task to conduct additional iterations of risk-informed planning process to distinguish among alternatives, identify TSP, and identify potential LPP if applicable.
Task to identify potential policy exceptions required by ASA(CW), including 3x3 exception, LPP waiver, etc.
Task to update PMP and review plan to document scope and schedule to final report transmittal.

n.d: Task to complete Legal Sufficiency Review of Draft Feasibility Report and NEPA document by district counsel.

Task to secure ASA(CW) exception if there is no NED plan generating a positive economic benefit-cost ratio.

Task to conduct Public and Agency Review of Draft Feasibility Report and NEPA document.

n.d: Task to complete Policy and Legal Compliance Review of Draft Feasibility Report and NEPA document with comments documented in a Project Guidance Memorandum.

Task to update PMP and review plan to document scope and schedule including proposed level of detail to final report transmittal.
